ions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMacrolide antibiotics (including erythromycin, azithromycin, and clarithromycin) are primarily effective against gram-positive organisms and atypical bacteria. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E (Group A Streptococcus) is typically susceptible to macrolides, making them a suitable alternative for patients with penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gram-negative organisms listed are generally not susceptible to macrolides due to their outer membrane structure which prevents the drug from reaching its target site, and the presence of efflux pumps that actively remove the drug:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E - intrinsically resistant to macrolides\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E - naturally resistant to macrolides\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E - inherently resistant to macrolides\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EProteus mirabilis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E - not susceptible to macrolides\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMacrolides work by binding to the 50S ribosomal subunit of bacteria, inhibiting protein synthesis. They are particularly useful for treating respiratory tract infections, skin infections, and infections caused by atypical organisms such as \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Macrolide antibiotics are primarily effective against gram-positive bacteria and atypical organisms.","Macrolides work by binding to the 50S ribosomal subunit to inhibit bacterial protein synthesis.","Streptococcus pyogenes is typically susceptible to macrolide antibiotics.","Gram-negative bacteria are generally resistant to macrolides due to their outer membrane structure and efflux pumps."],"references":["Patel PH, Hashmi MF. Macrolides. [Updated 2023 May 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551495/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52306"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15013"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52306"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T21:16:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T21:19:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7701"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66852"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving in